    "result": {"data":{"markdownRemark":{"html":"<p>On the OS level there are two most common <strong>units of execution</strong>:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>processes</li>\n<li>threads</li>\n</ul>\n<h2 id=\"process\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#process\" aria-label=\"process permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Process</h2>\n<p>A process has a self-contained execution environment. In particular, <strong>it has its own memory space</strong>!</p>\n<p>It takes longer to set up and it is usually a synonym for program/application.</p>\n<p>Processes can communicate via Inter Process Communication (IPC) protocols supported by the OS:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>pipes</li>\n<li>sockets</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The JVM is, in general, a single process.</p>\n<h2 id=\"thread\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#thread\" aria-label=\"thread permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Thread</h2>\n<p>We can understand a thread as a \"lightweight process\".</p>\n<p>Threads exist within a process and every process has at least one thread.</p>\n<p><strong>Threads share the process's resources, including memory and open files</strong>. Because of that, creating a new thread requires fewer resources than creating a new process.</p>\n<p>In Java, a program starts with a single thread, <strong>the main thread</strong>, but can create new ones.</p>\n<p><img src=\"/4578db7a3d1e80b2a03756467f1aeb76/multithreading.jpg\" alt=\"\"></p>\n<h2 id=\"thread-states\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#thread-states\" aria-label=\"thread states permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Thread states</h2>\n<p>In Java, the life cycle of a thread is controlled by the JVM:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>New</strong>: a thread which has not yet started</li>\n<li><strong>Runnable</strong>: a thread which is executing in the Java virtual machine but may be waiting for other resources from the operating system</li>\n<li><strong>Blocked</strong>: a thread which is waiting for a monitor lock to (re)enter a synchronized block/method</li>\n<li><strong>Waiting</strong>: a thread which is waiting for another thread to perform a particular action</li>\n<li><strong>Timed Waiting</strong>: a thread which is waiting for a specified amount of time</li>\n<li><strong>Terminated</strong>: a thread which has completed execution.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 625px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/f8dc75e46bc24e39a27c02ca21aeb2d6/dfe3c/thread-life-cycle.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 58.00000000000001%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"thread life cycle\"\n        title=\"thread life cycle\"\n        src=\"/static/f8dc75e46bc24e39a27c02ca21aeb2d6/dfe3c/thread-life-cycle.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/static/f8dc75e46bc24e39a27c02ca21aeb2d6/e07e9/thread-life-cycle.jpg 200w,\n/static/f8dc75e46bc24e39a27c02ca21aeb2d6/066f9/thread-life-cycle.jpg 400w,\n/static/f8dc75e46bc24e39a27c02ca21aeb2d6/dfe3c/thread-life-cycle.jpg 625w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 625px) 100vw, 625px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n        decoding=\"async\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<h2 id=\"thread-types\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#thread-types\" aria-label=\"thread types permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Thread types</h2>\n<p>It is important that we distinguish between two thread types:</p>\n<p><strong>User threads</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>High-priority threads</li>\n<li>The JVM will wait for any user thread to complete its task before terminating it</li>\n<li>E.g. Main thread</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Daemon threads</strong>:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Low-priority threads</li>\n<li>The JVM will terminate all daemon threads when all user threads terminate</li>\n<li>Their only role is to provide services to user threads</li>\n<li>E.g. Garbage collector</li>\n</ul>","frontmatter":{"slug":"/multithreading/processes-threads","title":"Processes & Threads","course":"Programming Project 2021/22","previous":"/multithreading/concurrency","next":"/multithreading/multithreading-java","chapter":18,"section":2,"module":"Multithreading","banner":null}}},"pageContext":{"slug":"/multithreading/processes-threads"}},
